So, you guys will actually be the first to
unveil this.

00:46:08.720 --> 00:46:14.319
This is the diagram for the, or the elevations
for the new Stone Hotel.

00:46:14.319 --> 00:46:19.650
It's across the street from our brewery--or
will be--approximately two years from now.

00:46:19.650 --> 00:46:20.880
Hopefully, just under.

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:23.240
We'll be breaking ground this summer.

00:46:23.240 --> 00:46:26.090
Forty-eight rooms and a couple of unique features.

00:46:26.090 --> 00:46:32.580
For example, each room will have a balcony
about five feet deep and 12 or 14 feet wide.

00:46:32.580 --> 00:46:36.820
And on a nice day, you push a button and the
garage door that separates you from the outside

00:46:36.820 --> 00:46:38.500
will roll up.

00:46:38.500 --> 00:46:43.510
And just completely bleeding indoors and outdoors.

00:46:43.510 --> 00:46:45.400
We won't have a check-in desk.

00:46:45.400 --> 00:46:47.859
So, what do you do when you want your room
key?

00:46:47.859 --> 00:46:52.170
Well, go to the bar of course.

00:46:52.170 --> 00:46:53.530
[laughter]

00:46:53.530 --> 00:46:57.250
You traveled to come here, so that's why you
need a hotel room and we figure you must be

00:46:57.250 --> 00:46:59.130
thirsty.

00:46:59.130 --> 00:47:01.019
[laughter]

00:47:01.019 --> 00:47:04.900
And we'll have event space there intermixed
with a barrel aging room.

00:47:04.900 --> 00:47:10.740
We're really, really ramping up our barrel
age program from spare barrels and also going

00:47:10.740 --> 00:47:13.690
to be producing a number of sours.

00:47:13.690 --> 00:47:15.250
We're very excited about that.

00:47:15.250 --> 00:47:16.510
Me, well, everybody.

00:47:16.510 --> 00:47:21.849
But I first got the chance to visit Cantillon
in 1995, the year before we opened Stone.

00:47:21.849 --> 00:47:25.832
So, I've been a fan of Belgian sour styles,
traditional sour styles for a long, long,

00:47:25.832 --> 00:47:26.832
long time.

00:47:26.832 --> 00:47:30.500
So, it's been a long time coming as far as
I'm concerned.

00:47:30.500 --> 00:47:32.050
[pause]

00:47:32.050 --> 00:47:35.599
And another two acres of outdoor space for
specialty beer festivals and specialty beer

00:47:35.599 --> 00:47:36.980
events.

00:47:36.980 --> 00:47:42.359
And if anybody's thinking about getting married
or something, we'll accommodate you.

00:47:42.359 --> 00:47:43.359
[laughter]

00:47:43.359 --> 00:47:45.890
&gt;&gt;Randy Clemens: And all good stuff.

00:47:45.890 --> 00:47:50.460
And I mean, if you can wax poetical a little
about just where you see the beer industry

00:47:50.460 --> 00:47:51.730
going and continuing to go.

00:47:51.730 --> 00:47:56.900
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Well, that slide, we're showing
the dip and the rise of the number of breweries

00:47:56.900 --> 00:47:57.900
in the United States.

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:03.759
We now have somewhere over 22 hundred craft
breweries or breweries--the majority or vast

00:48:03.759 --> 00:48:09.460
majority, which are craft breweries here in
the United States--with another 700 currently

00:48:09.460 --> 00:48:12.009
on file in planning.

00:48:12.009 --> 00:48:13.210
[pause]

00:48:13.210 --> 00:48:15.940
This is incredible.

00:48:15.940 --> 00:48:19.029
When Stone opened, there were about 800 breweries
in the United States.

00:48:19.029 --> 00:48:25.310
And then, there was the downturn period where
as many were closing as were opening for a

00:48:25.310 --> 00:48:26.490
number of years.

00:48:26.490 --> 00:48:29.020
And now, we're in the age of nano.

00:48:29.020 --> 00:48:35.130
We're in the age of continued, small breweries
opening up and yeah.

00:48:35.130 --> 00:48:36.130
Where will that go?

00:48:36.130 --> 00:48:37.130
I don't know.

00:48:37.130 --> 00:48:39.039
It's really, it's fascinating.

00:48:39.039 --> 00:48:43.150
Three years ago, the--it is.

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:48.400
Three years ago, the average American lived
within ten miles of a brewery.

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:50.390
That was three years ago.

00:48:50.390 --> 00:48:55.450
That was probably a solid 500 breweries ago.

00:48:55.450 --> 00:49:01.230
So, you could probably do a little guess work
on the math and think it's now within seven

00:49:01.230 --> 00:49:05.160
miles the average American lives within a
brewery.

00:49:05.160 --> 00:49:10.130
What can the United States, what can the market
bear?

00:49:10.130 --> 00:49:15.190
I think we can handle a tremendous amount
of growth.

00:49:15.190 --> 00:49:17.700
And I think things look really good.

00:49:17.700 --> 00:49:23.319
Right now, craft beer represents about five
percent of the market.

00:49:23.319 --> 00:49:24.880
And I think we can hit easy 20 percent.

00:49:24.880 --> 00:49:27.130
What do you guys think?

00:49:27.130 --> 00:49:28.599
Yeah?

00:49:28.599 --> 00:49:30.079
[clapping]

00:49:30.079 --> 00:49:32.770
Together we are heavy.

00:49:32.770 --> 00:49:33.770
[laughter]

00:49:33.770 --> 00:49:36.200
And it's exciting times.

00:49:36.200 --> 00:49:42.410
I do just have a word to all the young brewers
who are starting up.

00:49:42.410 --> 00:49:43.799
Be true to yourself.

00:49:43.799 --> 00:49:45.789
Be true to craft beer.

00:49:45.789 --> 00:49:48.119
Be true to the customers.

00:49:48.119 --> 00:49:51.980
Don't try and chase after customers by doing
what you think they might want.

00:49:51.980 --> 00:49:54.980
Try and do what you think is the right job.

00:49:54.980 --> 00:49:59.490
And then, if you're good at it, people will
gravitate towards your beer.

00:49:59.490 --> 00:50:07.480
But we have to be careful with so many breweries
opening up that we don't allow some of our

00:50:07.480 --> 00:50:10.410
ranks to do things that bring all of us down.

00:50:10.410 --> 00:50:15.660
And I don't think that that has to happen,
but I have a little bit of a fear it might

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:20.339
because if there's a bump in the road with
so much capacity and so many players out there,

00:50:20.339 --> 00:50:23.970
that some might resort to desperate measures.

00:50:23.970 --> 00:50:27.569
Stay strong, brothers and sisters.

00:50:27.569 --> 00:50:31.539
&gt;&gt;Randy Clemens: With that, our part of the
presentation is done.

00:50:31.539 --> 00:50:36.530
We can certainly open up to a couple questions
for Greg and I guess if you have some for

00:50:36.530 --> 00:50:37.530
me.

00:50:37.530 --> 00:50:39.359
But mostly if you have them for Greg.

00:50:39.359 --> 00:50:40.599
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Hi.

00:50:40.599 --> 00:50:46.529
So you were saying that you wanna make beers
that you love and also that you really love

00:50:46.529 --> 00:50:49.460
trying other craft beers.

00:50:49.460 --> 00:50:54.340
So, how strong is the temptation when you're
having somebody else's beer to like have some,

00:50:54.340 --> 00:50:55.809
"Oh, that's really good.

00:50:55.809 --> 00:50:56.849
I should make this."

00:50:56.849 --> 00:51:01.400
Like, how do you prevent yourself from trying
to make everybody else's beer if you're trying

00:51:01.400 --> 00:51:03.059
to make beer that you love?

00:51:03.059 --> 00:51:05.280
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: So, that's a great question.

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:09.440
I could answer it from a music perspective
'cause I came from the music industry before

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:10.440
brewing.

00:51:10.440 --> 00:51:12.410
So, I'll give you a music analogy.

00:51:12.410 --> 00:51:17.829
If you're a musician and you hear a song that
you love from somebody else, you don't necessarily

00:51:17.829 --> 00:51:22.190
want to try and copy that, but you can love
it and respect it just as much.

00:51:22.190 --> 00:51:26.970
Sometimes, what you do is go, "Oh, but the
way they did this particular lick or this

00:51:26.970 --> 00:51:33.049
character of the song or the rhythm or something,
I think I know how I might use that in this

00:51:33.049 --> 00:51:36.690
other thing that I had in the back of my mind."

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:44.630
So, just like a jazz musician can have classical
and thrash metal influences, it may show their

00:51:44.630 --> 00:51:48.809
own little way through into the jazz that
they play.

00:51:48.809 --> 00:51:53.050
We can sometimes be influenced by things that
you don't really see the connection to it,

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:55.279
but it filters through us creatively.

00:51:55.279 --> 00:52:00.280
And this is the same with any artisanal endeavor
I think.

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:01.900
So, no.

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:07.880
I think we're often inspired, but rarely want
to copy.

00:52:07.880 --> 00:52:09.890
There are some out there that are copying.

00:52:09.890 --> 00:52:14.890
Hey, I don't wanna say like, "Well,--."

00:52:14.890 --> 00:52:21.210
This doesn't suggest any copying because we
weren't the first ever to brew a double IPA,

00:52:21.210 --> 00:52:27.980
but just to give you a perspective, Stone
Ruination IPA, when it came out in June of

00:52:27.980 --> 00:52:32.960
2002, three, two, three, two.

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:33.960
Two.

00:52:33.960 --> 00:52:34.960
Two.

00:52:34.960 --> 00:52:37.430
OK, where was I?

00:52:37.430 --> 00:52:41.960
So, Stone Ruination IPA, which came out in
June 2002 was the first full-time brewed and

00:52:41.960 --> 00:52:44.460
bottled double IPA on the planet.

00:52:44.460 --> 00:52:45.891
Not the first ever one that was ever brewed.

00:52:45.891 --> 00:52:49.640
It was in, like, the first five arguably.

00:52:49.640 --> 00:52:55.839
And now, how many double IPAs, how many breweries
are making double IPAs?

00:52:55.839 --> 00:52:57.520
Were they copying us?

00:52:57.520 --> 00:52:58.520
No.

00:52:58.520 --> 00:53:00.980
But did we get inspired by, "Wow.

00:53:00.980 --> 00:53:02.529
A beer can be uber-hoppy.

00:53:02.529 --> 00:53:04.339
It can be super aromatic.

00:53:04.339 --> 00:53:09.279
It can be a lot stronger than I thought people
would want to ever drink."

00:53:09.279 --> 00:53:14.990
Because the average ABD was so much lower
at that time.

00:53:14.990 --> 00:53:17.619
And we get inspired.

00:53:17.619 --> 00:53:19.859
We do new things and we go in that direction.

00:53:19.859 --> 00:53:20.859
[pause]

00:53:20.859 --> 00:53:22.440
So, that's your answer.

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:23.440
[pause]

00:53:23.440 --> 00:53:25.539
&gt;&gt;Male #5: Well, if your--

00:53:25.539 --> 00:53:28.550
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: No, let's get the mic.

00:53:28.550 --> 00:53:35.910
&gt;&gt;Male #5: I'm from San Diego, so I have a
huge appreciation for you guys.

00:53:35.910 --> 00:53:40.000
Also a home-brewer Do you guys have, are you
growing your own hops at your--?

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:42.220
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: At the farm?

00:53:42.220 --> 00:53:43.220
&gt;&gt;Male #5: The farm.

00:53:43.220 --> 00:53:46.290
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: That's a question of do we grow
our own hops at Stone Farms?

00:53:46.290 --> 00:53:50.190
The answer is only on a very, very anecdotal
basis.

00:53:50.190 --> 00:53:53.589
We don't really have a functional hop growing
region in San Diego.

00:53:53.589 --> 00:53:59.150
It is in the Pacific Northwest, where they
have longer days during the summer.

00:53:59.150 --> 00:54:01.849
And just better overall micro-climate for
that.

00:54:01.849 --> 00:54:08.990
So, we can better grow our veggies and service
the restaurant that way than growing hops,

00:54:08.990 --> 00:54:09.990
which--.

00:54:09.990 --> 00:54:13.099
We're losing money growing veggies at Stone
Farms.

00:54:13.099 --> 00:54:15.980
We would really lose money growing hops at
Stone Farms.

00:54:15.980 --> 00:54:20.081
And I'm not sure we'd get the yield or the
quality or the character that we would want

00:54:20.081 --> 00:54:21.081
out of it.

00:54:21.081 --> 00:54:22.809
&gt;&gt;Male #5: My follow-up is, do you have a
favorite hop?

00:54:22.809 --> 00:54:25.069
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Do I have a favorite hop?

00:54:25.069 --> 00:54:26.069
Wow.

00:54:26.069 --> 00:54:27.069
I don't actually--.

00:54:27.069 --> 00:54:29.630
I usually get the old, "What's your favorite
beer?"

00:54:29.630 --> 00:54:32.650
question, which is an impossible question
to answer.

00:54:32.650 --> 00:54:36.630
So, just for if anybody was thinking of asking
it.

00:54:36.630 --> 00:54:38.609
Favorite hop.

00:54:38.609 --> 00:54:40.029
No.

00:54:40.029 --> 00:54:45.109
But I do have--.

00:54:45.109 --> 00:54:50.089
I can mention some new hop styles which, I
think, are capturing my imagination and I

00:54:50.089 --> 00:54:52.160
think a lot of people's imagination.

00:54:52.160 --> 00:54:54.279
Citra hops qualify.

00:54:54.279 --> 00:55:00.130
Amarillo, which isn't quite brand new, but
it's recent.

00:55:00.130 --> 00:55:02.280
Those are a couple hops that I really love.

00:55:02.280 --> 00:55:03.520
How about you, Randy?

00:55:03.520 --> 00:55:05.069
&gt;&gt;Randy Clemens: I'll say Nelson.

00:55:05.069 --> 00:55:06.069
Nelson Sauvin.

00:55:06.069 --> 00:55:07.069
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Nelson Sauvin.

00:55:07.069 --> 00:55:08.069
Yeah.

00:55:08.069 --> 00:55:13.720
And when you go historically back, the beers
that are being brewed today could not have

00:55:13.720 --> 00:55:15.650
been brewed historically.

00:55:15.650 --> 00:55:17.369
They didn't exist.

00:55:17.369 --> 00:55:23.589
While IPAs as a category have been around
for over a hundred years, originating in the

00:55:23.589 --> 00:55:30.240
UK, they couldn't have tasted like they do
today because the hop varieties that are in

00:55:30.240 --> 00:55:32.890
existence today were literally non-existent.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:37.259
Cascade hops didn't even come around until
the '60s.

00:55:37.259 --> 00:55:41.339
And what's different about the hops today
versus the noble varieties, the traditional

00:55:41.339 --> 00:55:53.380
European varieties, are the big citrusy, piney,
floral, sometimes tropical fruit aromas that

00:55:53.380 --> 00:55:55.190
you can get out of these varieties today.

00:55:55.190 --> 00:55:57.500
They just didn't exist.

00:55:57.500 --> 00:55:59.549
So, yeah.

00:55:59.549 --> 00:56:02.980
It's a fascinating, wonderful time of actual
new discovery.

00:56:02.980 --> 00:56:08.200
I can say that we are actually--music analogy
again--writing new songs that couldn't have

00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:10.499
been written.

00:56:10.499 --> 00:56:13.069
Sometimes you say, "Every note has been played.

00:56:13.069 --> 00:56:18.859
Every bit of music has already been created
before and we're just rehashing."

00:56:18.859 --> 00:56:22.420
And you can say that about brewing from one
angle, but from another angle you can say

00:56:22.420 --> 00:56:23.420
no.

00:56:23.420 --> 00:56:24.420
That's not true.

00:56:24.420 --> 00:56:26.660
We're actually creating new styles that couldn't
have possibly existed.

00:56:26.660 --> 00:56:30.700
You couldn't get the flavor and aromatic profiles
of many of the beers that are being brewed

00:56:30.700 --> 00:56:33.290
by craft brewers today, historically.

00:56:33.290 --> 00:56:34.290
[pause]

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:41.529
&gt;&gt;Male #6: How do you explain such a renaissance
of craft beer scene in San Diego and a full

00:56:41.529 --> 00:56:43.960
out wipe-out happen in Los Angeles?

00:56:43.960 --> 00:56:45.809
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: I can actually answer that.

00:56:45.809 --> 00:56:56.420
I lived in Los Angeles for 12 years, from
'84 to, I guess it was 11 years now that I'm

00:56:56.420 --> 00:56:57.490
doing that.

00:56:57.490 --> 00:56:58.490
'95.

00:56:58.490 --> 00:57:03.539
And craft beer got an early start in Los Angeles,
but it was a rocky start.

00:57:03.539 --> 00:57:11.859
Wolfgang Puck started his Eureka Brewing Company,
which was a very notable failure.

00:57:11.859 --> 00:57:15.930
And there was Rhino Chasers, which was a contract
brewed brand that was based out of the Los

00:57:15.930 --> 00:57:17.700
Angeles region.

00:57:17.700 --> 00:57:19.839
Also ended up being a notable failure.

00:57:19.839 --> 00:57:23.690
Gorky's, which was around, ended up failing.

00:57:23.690 --> 00:57:25.529
Anybody ever go to Gorky's back in the day?

00:57:25.529 --> 00:57:26.529
One.

00:57:26.529 --> 00:57:27.529
Awesome.

00:57:27.529 --> 00:57:28.529
I was there, too.

00:57:28.529 --> 00:57:29.529
&gt;&gt;Male #6: Not far from Al's.

00:57:29.529 --> 00:57:30.529
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Not far from Al's Bar.

00:57:30.529 --> 00:57:31.529
That's right.

00:57:31.529 --> 00:57:32.529
[laughter]

00:57:32.529 --> 00:57:33.529
You guys think I'm lousy.

00:57:33.529 --> 00:57:34.529
Downtown LA.

00:57:34.529 --> 00:57:37.890
And there were some beach breweries within
the beach area of Los Angeles.

00:57:37.890 --> 00:57:41.740
They were really brewing mediocre beer and
some of them were just faking it with fake

00:57:41.740 --> 00:57:45.530
takes and actually having the beer contract
brewed for them.

00:57:45.530 --> 00:57:50.670
There was so much going on in the beer industry--the
craft brewing industry--in LA that wasn't

00:57:50.670 --> 00:57:56.509
real or failed notably that it put a pall
on LA for a number of years.

00:57:56.509 --> 00:58:01.640
So, when Steve and I both were looking at
starting a brewery, we thought to ourselves,

00:58:01.640 --> 00:58:03.920
"We don't wanna this in LA.

00:58:03.920 --> 00:58:06.779
This is not a good place for craft beer."

00:58:06.779 --> 00:58:14.799
And that's why we moved down to San Diego
because we thought there was more of an opportunity.

00:58:14.799 --> 00:58:15.799
[pause]

00:58:15.799 --> 00:58:16.799
But then, now why San Diego?

00:58:16.799 --> 00:58:23.390
So, in San Diego, we have had the luck of
having a number of really amazing quality

00:58:23.390 --> 00:58:28.430
inspired, creative brewers.

00:58:28.430 --> 00:58:34.480
And I think if we've done anything at Stone,
is we helped set the example that you could

00:58:34.480 --> 00:58:37.089
go where the market wasn't.

00:58:37.089 --> 00:58:40.970
And the market didn't think it wanted to go
or didn't know it wanted to go.

00:58:40.970 --> 00:58:44.019
And you could go that direction and you could
be successful with it.

00:58:44.019 --> 00:58:51.390
So, as other brewers saw us taking all these
left turns and going big and going odd and

00:58:51.390 --> 00:58:54.540
such, other breweries said, "Wait.

00:58:54.540 --> 00:58:55.540
Well, you know?

00:58:55.540 --> 00:59:05.839
We'll break out of the amber ale, golden ale,
hefeweizen, dry stout, and premium golden

00:59:05.839 --> 00:59:09.549
ale categories and start branching out into
more unique styles."

00:59:09.549 --> 00:59:12.299
&gt;&gt;Randy Clemens: And I'll add in real quick.

00:59:12.299 --> 00:59:14.560
Just, I mean, there is great stuff happening
now in LA.

00:59:14.560 --> 00:59:18.480
I mean, you got, certainly there's great beer
bars, but Craftsman Brewing Company up in

00:59:18.480 --> 00:59:19.480
Pasadena has been there since 1995.

00:59:19.480 --> 00:59:20.480
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Yeah.

00:59:20.480 --> 00:59:23.109
&gt;&gt;Randy Clemens: You've got Eagle Rock Brewery
that's open in Eagle Rock a few years ago,

00:59:23.109 --> 00:59:24.490
a little over two years ago.

00:59:24.490 --> 00:59:26.289
El Segundo, really close to here.

00:59:26.289 --> 00:59:27.670
Rob's doing some great stuff there.

00:59:27.670 --> 00:59:28.920
His Wheat IPA is fantastic.

00:59:28.920 --> 00:59:31.420
His Hyperion's Stout's great.

00:59:31.420 --> 00:59:32.500
And there's other people.

00:59:32.500 --> 00:59:35.230
If you're up Agoura Hills way, there's Ladyface
Ale Companie.

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:36.720
There's some really cool stuff happening now.

00:59:36.720 --> 00:59:40.950
And I think there might be something again
its infancy.

00:59:40.950 --> 00:59:45.730
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: I think LA is coming into its
renaissance time for craft beer definitely.

00:59:45.730 --> 00:59:48.720
This is good time.

00:59:48.720 --> 00:59:49.720
I think all the way in the back.

00:59:49.720 --> 00:59:50.720
Last, a last--.

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:51.720
&gt;&gt;Male #7: Is there a East Coast/West Coast
rivalry?

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:52.720
I'm from New England and I know there's a
lot of good craft beers up there.

00:59:52.720 --> 00:59:53.720
I feel like some of the ones back East taste
a little different.

00:59:53.720 --> 01:00:01.000
Is there a different styles or different--?

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:04.829
You talked about--.

01:00:04.829 --> 01:00:09.750
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Is there East Coast/West Coast
rivalry in craft brewing?

01:00:09.750 --> 01:00:15.789
Well, I worked with my friend, Sam, from Delaware
at Dogfish.

01:00:15.789 --> 01:00:21.859
I did take him into the hop cooler and feel
compelled to actually say, "By the way, these,

01:00:21.859 --> 01:00:23.599
we call them hops."

01:00:23.599 --> 01:00:24.609
[laughter]

01:00:24.609 --> 01:00:32.650
To which he said, "Oh, good one Greg."

01:00:32.650 --> 01:00:33.660
[laughter]

01:00:33.660 --> 01:00:34.960
Not so much rivalry.

01:00:34.960 --> 01:00:41.630
I think it's only poetry slam rivalry level,
which we have a lot of respect for each other.

01:00:41.630 --> 01:00:47.230
And we love throwing elbows and making fun,
but then give me another one of your delicious

01:00:47.230 --> 01:00:49.930
beers that you brew 'cause I really like what
you do.

01:00:49.930 --> 01:00:50.930
Yeah.

01:00:50.930 --> 01:00:54.849
&gt;&gt;Male #8: So, I had a baby about a year ago.

01:00:54.849 --> 01:00:56.250
My wife had the baby.

01:00:56.250 --> 01:00:57.250
[laughter]

01:00:57.250 --> 01:00:58.250
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: I'm glad you're clear on that.

01:00:58.250 --> 01:01:01.849
&gt;&gt;Male #8: And I had just thought stopped
home-brewing and I'd been drinking mostly

01:01:01.849 --> 01:01:05.309
Stone IPAs since then because damn they're
good.

01:01:05.309 --> 01:01:10.170
They're all just as good as my home-brew And
I--.

01:01:10.170 --> 01:01:15.089
Because what I discovered was the worst home-brew,
as long as it didn't skunk out, was better

01:01:15.089 --> 01:01:18.609
than almost any beer you could reliably find
except for Stone.

01:01:18.609 --> 01:01:24.089
So, what advice might you have for home-brewers
or things that home-brewers who want to get

01:01:24.089 --> 01:01:29.140
closer to what you guys are doing in terms
of density and richness and alcoholic content

01:01:29.140 --> 01:01:31.210
and that sort of thing?

01:01:31.210 --> 01:01:35.660
What are home-brewers not doing that they
could be doing to get a better beer?

01:01:35.660 --> 01:01:40.319
&gt;&gt;Greg Koch: Nice segue for buying our book,
which has home-brew recipes in it.

01:01:40.319 --> 01:01:41.319
[laughter]

01:01:41.319 --> 01:01:43.140
Or my other book called "The Brewer's Apprentice."

01:01:43.140 --> 01:01:44.140
But no.

01:01:44.140 --> 01:01:51.590
Other than showing my book, the answer to
that is as a home-brewer, the best piece of

01:01:51.590 --> 01:01:56.029
advice I can ever give: join a home-brew club.

01:01:56.029 --> 01:02:00.259
Start home-brewing with somebody else just
like I did with Steve, who was much more advanced

01:02:00.259 --> 01:02:02.940
at the time we started home-brewing when we
worked together than I was.

01:02:02.940 --> 01:02:05.980
So, I had the benefit from learning from somebody
else.

01:02:05.980 --> 01:02:08.079
And he had learned from a friend of his.

01:02:08.079 --> 01:02:12.290
So, instead of just opening up a book, no
matter how brilliantly written and well-designed

01:02:12.290 --> 01:02:15.000
it might be,--

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:17.339
[laughter]

01:02:17.339 --> 01:02:20.869
get together with friends because brewing,
home-brewing with friends, of course, is a

01:02:20.869 --> 01:02:21.930
great way to do it.

01:02:21.930 --> 01:02:25.400
And you amplify your learning curve by doing
what people who have been doing it.

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:30.650
So, I recommend get together with home-brewers
And the American Home-brewers Association--fantastic

01:02:30.650 --> 01:02:32.109
resource for that.

